ife took much of its shape from the arrival of Irish and Jewish immigrants in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, and Forged in America is the story of how Irish America and Jewish America collided, cooperated, and collaborated in the cities where they made their homes, all the while shaping American identity and nationhood as we know it.Bringing together leading scholars in their fields, this volume sheds light on the underexplored histories of Irish and Jewish collaboration. While mutual antagonism was clearly evident, so too were opportunities for cooperation, as settled Irish immigrants served to model, mentor, and mediate for Jewish newcomers. Together, the chapters in this volume draw fascinating portraits that show mutuality in action and demonstrate its cultural reverberations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIrish AmericansxHistory. 0aIrish AmericansxRelations with Jews. 0aJewszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  abooks on irish culture.  abooks on irish history.  abooks on irish immigration to america.  abooks on jewish culture.  abooks on jewish history.  airish american history books.  airish american history facts.  airish american history.  ajewish american history books.  ajewish american history facts.  ajewish american history.1 aBaron, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrett, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasey, Marion R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiner, Hasia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiner, Hasia R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGary, Brett, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolway, Terry, 